<raw><![CDATA[    Investing.com – The U.S. dollar was broadly higher against its major counterparts on Monday, as the euro turned sharply lower amid ongoing worries over the debt crisis in the single currency bloc.During European afternoon trade, the greenback was higher against the euro, with EUR/USD shedding 0.56% to hit 1.4124.The single currency came under broad selling pressure after Chancellor Angela Merkel's ruling party were defeated in local elections on Sunday. The result may hamper efforts to grant new powers to the euro zone's bailout fund, ahead of a ruling on the legality of the latest bailout for Greece, due to be handed down by Germany’s constitutional court later in the week.The greenback was also higher against the pound, with GBP/USD falling 0.45% to hit 1.6141.Earlier in the day, a report showed that service sector activity in the U.K. posted the biggest drop in more than a decade in August, adding to expectations that the Bank of England will leave interest rates on hold well into next year.Meanwhile, the greenback inched higher against the yen but was down against the Swiss franc, with USD/JPY easing up 0.10% to hit 76.88 and USD/CHF dropping 0.15% to hit 0.7870.Earlier Monday, Japan’s new Finance Minister Jun Azumi said the strong yen was damaging to both Japan and the global economy and reiterated Japan’s readiness to intervene in currency markets to weaken the currency.Elsewhere, the greenback was higher against its Canadian, Australian and New Zealand counterparts, with USD/CAD rising 0.31% to hit 0.9882, AUD/USD shedding 0.69% to hit 1.0569 and NZD/USD tumbling 1.30% to hit 0.8369.Earlier Monday, official data showed that Australian company profits rose sharply in the second quarter, due to the country’s mining boom. A separate report showed that Australia’s service sector expanded in August, after contracting in the two previous months.The dollar index, which tracks the performance of the greenback versus a basket of six other major currencies, rose 0.42% to hit 75.14.Also Monday, markets in the U.S. were to remain closed for the Labor Day holiday.             ]]></raw>
